● Perfect, I can see the certificate configuration:

  Certificate Details:
  - CN: serviceregistry.c1.ltu.arrowhead.eu
  - SANs (Subject Alternative Names):
    - DNS: serviceregistry, c1-serviceregistry, localhost
    - IP: 127.0.0.1

  The Problem

  When you connect from another host using the server's IP address (e.g., 192.168.1.100:8443), the TLS handshake will fail because:

  1. The certificate only has 127.0.0.1 in its IP SAN
  2. Your client will try to validate the certificate against 192.168.1.100
  3. The validation fails → connection refused

  Solutions

  Option 1: Regenerate Certificates with Host IP (Recommended)

  Add your server's IP address to the certificate SANs when generating them:

  # In the certificate generation script, add:
  SAN=DNS:serviceregistry,DNS:c1-serviceregistry,DNS:localhost,IP:127.0.0.1,IP:<YOUR_SERVER_IP>

  Option 2: Use DNS Hostname (Best for Production)

  Instead of IP, use a hostname:

  1. Add DNS record: arrowhead-c1.yourdomain.com → <YOUR_SERVER_IP>
  2. Regenerate certificates with that hostname in SANs
  3. Clients connect to https://arrowhead-c1.yourdomain.com:8443

  Option 3: SSH Port Forwarding (Quick Test)

  From the client machine:
  ssh -L 8443:localhost:8443 user@<YOUR_SERVER_IP>
  # Then connect to https://localhost:8443

  Option 4: Disable TLS Validation (INSECURE - Testing Only)

  Only for testing - never in production:
  # In your Arrowhead client
  curl -k https://<SERVER_IP>:8443/...

  The certificates are generated by the Arrowhead framework scripts. You'd need to regenerate them with the appropriate SANs for your deployment scenario. Which approach fits your
  use case?


